 to New York around 1800","body":"Around the turn of the nineteenth century he sold the Sheldon Moore homestead in Kensington and moved to Madison County, New York — to either Whitestown or De Ruyter. He died there around 1811, more than a decade after the move."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"His grandson became America's foremost 1820s poet","body":"His grandson James Gates Percival (1795-1856) — son of daughter Elizabeth and Dr. James Percival Jr. — became the most recognized American poet of the 1820s and Connecticut's first state geologist. James was born in Kensington before Matthew Hart Jr. departed for New York."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"Born after his father had died","body":"Matthew Hart was born in January 1737, weeks after his father died the previous October. He grew up to serve as a Revolutionary corporal and later removed to New York."}],"slug":"matthew-hart-jr-1737"},"X01933":{"id":"X01933","has_descendants_documented":false,"is_placeholder":false,"gender":"female","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1740,"month":11,"day":29,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1817,"month":1,"day":1},"parents":{},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00286","children_ids":["H00607","H00608","H00609","H00610","H00611","H00612"],"date_year":1759,"date_month":11,"date_day":15,"location_city":"Farmington","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909; Hart Genealogy 1948"}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Elizabeth Hopkins Hart","first_name":"Elizabeth","last_name":"Hart","maiden_name":"Hopkins","married_names":["Hart"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[